-- Stocks, Copper Slide on China Rate Concern; Treasuries Tumble
-- B y   S t e p h e n   K i r k l a n d
-- 2010-11-12T10:39:41Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-12/asian-stocks-won-zinc-drop-on-g-20-trade-talks-china-inflation-concerns.html
Stocks  declined, sending Europe’s
benchmark index down the most in seven weeks, while U.S. futures
and commodities fell on speculation China will raise interest
rates. The yen strengthened and 30-year Treasury bonds rallied.  The Stoxx Europe 600 Index slumped 0.9 percent at 10:35
a.m. in London, heading for the biggest one-day drop since Sept.
22. Futures on the  Standard & Poor’s 500 Index  lost 0.7 percent.
The yen appreciated against all 16 of its most-traded
counterparts. The yield on the 30-year bond fell 10 basis
points. The Spanish 10-year note yield climbed for the 14th day,
while similar-maturity Irish debt snapped a 13-day slide. The
S&P GSCI index of commodities sank the most in three weeks as
white sugar tumbled 12 percent and oil fell 2.3 percent.  China’s central bank may increase rates within weeks after
inflation accelerated to the fastest pace in 25 months in
October, according to economists surveyed by Bloomberg. Group of
20 leaders agreed to develop early warning indicators to head
off economic turmoil following emergency talks on Ireland’s debt
crisis, according to a statement from the Seoul summit. The
Federal Reserve is scheduled to start a second phase of bond
purchases today designed to revive the economy.  “China’s focus on containing inflation highlights the risk
that other nations will face in the wake of global easing and
rising commodity prices,” said  Olan Caperina , who helps manage
$11 billion at Bank of the Philippine Islands in Manilla.
“There are still lingering concerns the global economy remains
in a fragile state of recovery.”  Rio Tinto, Rolls-Royce  Three companies fell for every one that gained on the  Stoxx
600 , while all 19 industry groups retreated. Basic-resources
stocks led the selloff as metals declined, with Rio Tinto Group
sliding 2.9 percent and copper dropping 2.3 percent in London,
the most in two weeks.  Rolls-Royce Group Plc climbed 2.8 percent after saying
profit will only be “slightly lower” than previously forecast
on costs to rectify a failure in the Trent 900 engine that
grounded Qantas Airways Ltd.’s fleet of Airbus SAS A380s.  China’s  Shanghai Composite Index  sank 5.2 percent, its
biggest decline since August 2009. The  MSCI Emerging Markets
Index  fell 1.5 percent, with benchmark indexes in Poland, India,
the Philippines, Thailand and Taiwan retreating at least 1
percent. Banks led Turkey’s  National ISE 100 index  1.3 percent
lower after the central bank increased reserve levels for
lenders. Hungary’s  BUX  index gained 0.6 percent after a report
showed the economy accelerated last quarter more than economists
predicted.  Consumer Sentiment  The decline in  U.S. futures  indicated the S&P 500 may
extend the biggest weekly drop in three months. Confidence among
U.S. consumers probably improved in November for the first time
in three months, economists said before a report due at 9:55
a.m. New York time. The Thomson Reuters/University of Michigan
preliminary sentiment index rose to 69 from a final reading of
67.7 in October, according to the median forecast.  The Fed is  scheduled  to buy $6 billion to $8 billion of
U.S. government securities today, targeting those due from
November 2014 to April 2016, as part of $600 billion in
purchases through June to spur growth.  The yield on the 30-year Treasury was 4.24 percent. A sale
of $16 billion of 30-year bonds two days ago drew a bid-to-cover
ratio, which gauges demand by comparing total bids with the
amount of securities. The extra yield investors demand to hold
10-year Spanish bonds instead of benchmark German bunds gained
six basis points to 226 basis points, while the Irish-German
spread  narrowed  44 basis points to 602 basis points.  Italy sold 7.92 billion euros ($10.8 billion) of bonds
maturing in 2015, 2026 and 2034, less than the 8.25 billion
euros indicated before the sale. The yield on its 10-year note
rose seven basis points to 4.30 percent.  The S&P  GSCI  index of 24 commodities declined 2 percent,
the biggest drop since Oct. 19. White sugar futures fell as much
as $93.60 to $675 a metric ton after the European Union said it
plans to increase exports.  To contact the reporter on this story:
 Stephen Kirkland  in London at 
